PC generations can have very subjective
definitions. A generation is always defined
by the GPU, since in an ideal scenario the
GPU should be the defining bottleneck
hence limit for any given build. If the CPU,
RAM, or in some rare cases even the MB or
PSU are bottlenecks, then the build is not
properly configured in the first place.
GPUs are easiest to upgrade, so a build should always try to get the best CPU for the budget,
compromise on the GPU if at all, then upgrade it later. Upgrading the CPU or MB even
if doable, are more complicated and do not assure better gaming performance if old GPU
bottlenecks the new CPU. Alternately, if the bottlenecking old GPU is upgraded to a new one on
same CPU, it instantly gives a better measurable experience.
A factor that can loosely define a PC generation is the DirectX major version. Over the years,
DirectX has largely definied how games communicate with the GPUs from across vendors. Each
major version brought with it improvements in image quality, new features and API levels that
shaped the design of game code. Based on this, generations can be
Gen 1: up to DX9 - Windows XP (32bit)
However, in hindsight and also because of contemporary hardware, DX9 and DX10 can more or
less be managed by same CPU/ GPU. Rather, DX12 which has been the major DX version since the
last 10 years, actually oversees very different requirements that cannot be served by same class of
GPU, like upscaling (12.2) and now Frame Generation (12.3 or Ultimate). Hence it is better to
combine DX9 and DX10, and split DX12:
Gen 1: up to DX10 - Windows Vista (32 bit games/ apps run on 64bit, not vice versa)

A GPU may be used in several builds, each occurrence may play
several games. Same game with multiple GPU on same system
should result in two entries in Game Stats. In Playnite too, we can
do it by suffixing the Name with GPU
Items supported would be GPU and Controllers - these are likely
to be swapped in multiple builds, and directly impact gameplay.
Other hardware components need not be considered and would
unnecessarily make the soution too complex to maintain.
